\textbf{Key expected findings:} Stateless baselines fail under A2~and~A4 (temporal grinding): Krum, FoolsGold, FLTrust all show ASR $\ge 0.55$. Each layer's removal increases ASR by $\ge 10$~pp, with the largest drop from L3 removal (C5 vs.~C8: 0.50 vs.~0.25). Adaptive threshold adds $\sim$7~pp (C8 vs.~C9: 0.25 vs.~0.32), while the cascade structure contributes the majority of improvement (C9 vs.~C1: 0.32 vs.~0.92). Honest FPR $\sim$1.2\%, consistent with \S\ref{sec:analysis}.

% =====================================================================
\section{Formal Analysis}
\label{sec:analysis}
% =====================================================================

\subsection{Cascade Error Propagation Bound}
\label{sec:fpr-bound}

We bound the gated cascade's honest false positive rate. Let $\text{FPR}_k$ be the FPR of layer $k$. The cascade FPR is:

\begin{equation}
\text{FPR}_{\text{cascade}} = \text{FPR}_1 + (1 - \text{FPR}_1 - \text{TPR}_1) \cdot [\text{FPR}_2 + (1 - \text{FPR}_2 - \text{TPR}_2) \cdot \text{FPR}_3]
\end{equation}

\textbf{Stewart's perturbation bound~\cite{stewart1993}.} For matrix $A$ and its perturbation $A+E$: $|\lambda_k(A+E) - \lambda_k(A)| \le \|E\|_2$. Modeling honest updates as bounded perturbations of a reference, the reconstruction error $e_i^{(t)}$ for an honest client differs from the reference by at most $\|\Delta_i\|_2$.

Under bounded perturbations $\|\Delta_i\| \le \delta$, $k=3$ principal components, and $\tau_2 = 0.4$, $\delta \le 0.15$:

\begin{equation}
\mathbb{P}[e_i > \tau_2 \mid \text{honest}] \le 2 \cdot \exp\left(-\frac{(\tau_2 - \delta C)^2}{2\sigma^2}\right)
\end{equation}

giving $\text{FPR}_2 \le 0.012$. Combined with $\text{FPR}_1 \le 0.003$ and $\text{FPR}_3 \le 0.001$:

\begin{equation}
\text{FPR}_{\text{cascade}} \le 0.003 + (0.997 - \text{TPR}_1) \cdot [0.012 + (0.988 - \text{TPR}_2) \cdot 0.001] \approx 0.016
\end{equation}

\textbf{Implication.} The cascade maintains honest FPR $\le 1.6\%$ under bounded perturbations, bounding the feedback-loop risk.

\subsection{Convergence of Adaptive Threshold Dynamics}

The threshold update defines a dynamical system on $(\theta_{\text{high}}, \theta_{\text{low}})$:

\begin{equation}
\theta^{(t+1)} = \theta^{(t)} + \eta(t) \cdot h(\theta^{(t)}, \rho^{(t)})
\end{equation}

where $h$ captures the attack-response signal. Under stationary $\rho^{(t)}$ with mean $\rho_0$, the system converges to a neighborhood of $\theta^* = \{\theta : \rho(\theta) = \rho_0\}$.

\textbf{Lipschitz condition.} $h$ is Lipschitz with constant $L_h = |\eta_{\text{attack}} - \eta_{\text{relax}}| \cdot |\partial\rho/\partial\theta|$. For $\eta_{\text{attack}} = 0.15$, $\eta_{\text{relax}} = 0.05$, $|\partial\rho/\partial\theta| \le 0.5$: $L_h = 0.05 < 1$ (contraction).

\textbf{Neighborhood size.} $\|\theta^{(t)} - \theta^*\| \le O(\eta \sigma_\rho / (1 - L_h))$. For $\eta = 0.05$, $\sigma_\rho \le 0.1$, $L_h \le 0.05$: bound $\approx 0.0053$ ($\sim$0.5~pp of optimal). Under non-stationary attack patterns, the threshold tracks the moving optimum with bounded lag---characterized as a \textbf{control system}.

\subsection{Fairness Guarantee via Reputation Forgetting}

\textbf{Theorem~1 (Reputation Floor).} For any client with honest behavior ($a_i^{(t)} \ge 0.95$ for $t > t_0$):
\begin{equation}
\liminf_{t\to\infty} R_i^{(t)} \ge R_{\text{SS}} = 0.85
\end{equation}

\textit{Proof sketch.} With $a_i^{(t)} = 1$, the EMA update converges to $R = 1$. For the worst-case honest client with $a_i^{(t)} = 0.95$ and steady-state floor at $R_{\text{SS}} = 0.85$, reputation is bounded below by $R_{\text{SS}}$ regardless of transient false flags.

\textbf{Corollary~1 (Max Consecutive False Flags).} For honest clients, $\text{MCFF} \le t_0 = 20$ rounds. Since $R_{\text{SS}} > \tau_R$ ($\tau_R = 0.75$), reputation never drops below the rejection threshold.

\subsection{Privacy-Robustness Tension}

